Yes, `std::unique_ptr` automatically manages the deallocation, so you only own it until所有权 is explicitly transferred. Here is the corrected code where `std::make_unique` creates the smart pointer in the loop, and ownership is moved into `executeTrade` using `std::move`, ensuring the order is safely finalized:

```cpp
void processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {
    if (order && order->isValid()) {
        executeTrade(std::move(order)); // Ownership transfers here
    }
}

// In your main loop
auto newOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(data);
processOrder(std::move(newOrder)); // No need to 'delete', it handles cleanup
```

Ensure that your `executeTrade` function accepts the pointer by value (as `std::unique_ptr`) or by non-const reference to properly receive ownership; otherwise, it might leave the resource in an orphaned state.
